It's not clear which week you're in until you get to the end of each week and the game pauses, it would be good to have this displayed by the clock. Exiting the app relies on the Android swipe from the bottom to minimise and close the app rather than an exit option in the menu.

Mini Metro is more than anything else a planning game. You will build a metro network for several different cities, starting from just a few stations and ending up with tens of them and countless interchanges. At a certain point you will always lose, but the fun is about how big and efficient your metro network will become! It requires very smart planning and tactical decisions, but at the same time the smooth music and the ability to pause anytime makes is very relaxing. Great game! 😃🚄

I'm not kidding when I say the first time I tried this, I wound up playing it for four hours straight! I love the challenges on each level, especially since they are a) optional and b) easily set aside once you lose, so you can keep playing endlessly even when things inevitably go wrong.

This game is simple, in the sense of a minimalist premise: There are metro stations of different shapes. Stations slowly spawn passengers, whose destination is indicated by their shape. Use your fingers to draw lines between stations that your cars travel on. Every Sunday you'll get new assets - locomotives, train cars or the ability to create another line (instead of just adding more stations to existing ones). Sooner or later it becomes a race against collapse. Worth well over asking price! :)

It's a good port of the PC version, a game I already really enjoyed. I'd spent quite a few hours in the Steam release hoarding achievements. However, there is an issue here that I don't remember running into before; if you are trying to link two stations on the same side of a river, if the river bends in such a way that it comes between the two stations the game will not let you connect the stations. If you do have a tunnel, the tunnel will be used even though the stations are on the same side of the river! If you have no tunnel or do not want to use one, you should be able to have your line go around the bend of the river rather than wasting resources. I don't remember having this issue in the PC version but I've had it on almost every map I've played here. In the worst cases, I literally cannot connect lines to a new station and have to remove an existing tunnel to solve the issue. Unless I'm just being dumb and there is already an option for this. Love the game, would like to hear what's occuring with my issue.

Also, sometimes there are parameters or restrictions on a particular city that you're not aware of unless you try to do something that goes against those restrictions. For instance, in one city I tried to add a fifth locomotive to a line but a message popped up saying that city cannot have more than four per line . There was no way (that I'm aware of) to have known that. It'd be nice, while you're playing a city, for there to be a button you can tap on to review the unique rules for that city. I've completed the basic goal for each city (there's about 10 or 12 cities) and that's the only negative thing that I can come up with. Great game!

content:
Relaxing gameplay and stunningly good graphics and animation. Simple yet 
beautiful

Immensely frustrating, and not in a good way. While the game looks lovely, 
and the controls are superficially adequate, it becomes very difficult to 
redraw or extend routes when dealing with multiple lines on a densely 
populated map. The appearance of new stations seems to be random, passenger 
numbers can escalate totally without warning, and if the RNG hasn't given 
you favourable assets then your only hope of survival is frequently to 
redraw the whole map. Which wouldn't be a problem, were it not for the 
finicky controls I mentioned earlier. Endless mode removes that constant 
tension, but paradoxically the game really suffers without it. Extreme mode 
seems to have been added purely as a facetious nod to the ZOMG HARDCOAR 
crowd. Also, the music really creeps me out (YMMV, natch). Three words? 
British Rail pie.
Makes me wish I were a civil engineer.
It would be better if it supports Android O's adaptive icons.

it used to. Now it only shows other players. Also, somehow, with recent 
updates, it seems like the traffic increases more quickly and often beyond 
the scope of any possible resources, like a forced ceiling, almost.

The game is a good management game with simple systems and lots of variety 
of problems and solutions. Essentially, though, there is too much 
randomness and not enough ways to curb escalation. Passengers get added 
randomly so I don't know when or where to expect them; worst of all, I 
don't know which Stations are higher priority, so I have no idea which 
locations passengers will prefer. Stations get crowded very quickly in the 
mid-game, and there is no direct way for me to help that. The upgrades, 
although I get to select two, are always randomly paired. So even though I 
need a carriage, my only options might be new lines and new tunnels. 
Therefore, the loss condition is out of my hands, like a roll of the dice. 
This game feels very strategic and simple, but I worry there are underlying 
mechanics that I can't understand or predict. If I better knew why 
passengers want to go where they want to go or, for instance, why my trains 
sometimes just breeze past a bust station without picking anyone up, that 
would make the game more fair.

I really wanted to love this game. From reading reviews you would assume that it's a near perfect game. It suffers in a number of areas.   There's no tutorial. You start out with your entire knowledge about the game coming from what you read on Google Play. The game makes very little effort to educate you. After over an hour of play I still have no idea how half of it works. I have stations that fill up and give me a game over even though there are multiple lines connected and trains stop at the site.   I don't know the difference between a bridge and a tunnel. I don't know why a carriage is better than another train. I can't figure out how to build the city as there's little to tell you what makes a strategy work. There's just no feedback from the game other than sudden and unexplained losses.  I want to like this game, especially when I paid a premium price for it, but I have no idea what the actual goal is I'm shooting for.

Without an option to reverse a couple of seconds and avoid this error, it is a very calming and fun game to waste a little time. Also, in extreme mode, if the game adds a station in a place that requires a tunnel, you have to supply the tunnel as well, or you're mathematically dead. It spoils the fun of the game. Finally, every Sunday you should give the player the opportunity to choose a couple of items among all the possible choices (locomotive, line, tunnel, interchange, carriage) instead of two random items. This would allow the player to create its own strategy instead of hoping that she will get the interchange rather than a tunnel or whatever. After all, it's a puzzle game. Keep up the good work, this game has potential. Do non abandon it, create more different content, different kind of trains etc.

content: Brilliant time waster, this is my favourite game of the week.  It needs a snip tool for looped tracks to be cut at any point.  There's no opportunity to buy carriages etc. using credits from passengers.  Waiting until Monday doesn't seem fair when you get further into the game.

Thanks for the great game!

replyContent:
Hello Matt, 
We're really sorry you didn't like your experience. The music issue was due to the engine we're using and should now be fixed. Please, make sure to get the last update. 
Concerning the random, it's a design choice to add some challenge. Sorry you don't like it. You also can play on the endless mode that can be very refreshing and zen.

Amazing puzzle/simulation game with simple, yet effective graphics and terrific gameplay. Controls can get take a bit to get used to but are intuitive enough but to detract from gameplay for long. One of my favorite games of the year.

The game has all the features I believe a good mobile game should have. It has simple rules and mechanics, but still feels deep. The interface is simple, but feels polished. A round doesn't take too long to complete. Above all, it's fun and makes you think about how urban transport systems actually work.  Next time you're stuck in an overcrowded bus, you'll know: surely it's because there are too many damn circles and unique symbols bunched together on opposite parts of town. What else could it be?

replyContent:
Hello, 
Crossing water require to have a bridge, you can unlock some as time pass. Every color represent a different line. All the game is about creating and managing a subway network. And the challenge remains in the way you can adapt to your network evolution. I hope we have answered all your question. Best

replyContent:
Hi Kevin, 
The goal is to draw lines between stations (the different points on the city map) so that your trains reach them and all the passengers waiting at each station. The more passengers served the more points you get. You can add more upgrades over time, they will help you to increase your grid. But don't make passengers wait to much!

I bought the game not too long ago for Windows, though I had been familiar with it and played the in-browser demo for ages. As such, when I remembered there was an Android release, and that I had some google play money leftover from the holidays, I bought it here on the play store. Regardless of device, it's a great game, and I'm more than happy with my purchases. It handles just as well on android as I'd expect, though I run into a bit of a snag. Nothing too horrible, just a curiosity I'd like to bring to light.  My daily driver is not generally my phone, it's an Acer Chromebook R-11, which was one of the first models to support android apps/games out of the box. When I'm using the device's touchscreen to play the game, it works fine, and exactly as one might expect. However, when using the touchpad/trackpad/whatever-it's-called, it will work MOSTLY fine, but it's very prone to wigging out. Doesn't break the game, though sometimes rail lines stop being drawn onscreen after it attempts to recover from said fit. I don't think this is an issue many people will run into, as I do believe Chromebooks users are still largely a niche device compared to the likes of phones and tablets, and as such I'm not too upset. I'll continue to enjoy the game on all devices, even with that little hiccup.  Thanks for bringing it to Android (and thus ChromeOS)! I have many more hours to sink into this game. I've unlocked as far as Cairo on windows, and have much more ahead of me on Android!
A brilliant little game, supported it from the start and I'm so glad it's really come into its own.

The good:   This game is original, clever, simplistic, and artistic. Controls are simple and easy to learn. The procedurally generated stations typically result in maps that don't resemble the real cities, but that doesn't take away from the gameplay. Overall it's an amusing way to work your brain if you have 10 minutes of free time.   The bad:  It's repetitive. There is very little variance between levels, as the only major distinguishing factors are the bodies of water and whether a car can hold 4 or 6 passengers. Unlocking new levels is relatively unchallenging, and difficulty doesn't increase in later levels. The only thing you unlock is a new map to play on, without any added challenge or benefit. I found myself getting bored before I had even unlocked all the maps. There are also a few minor usability issues with the menus (e.g., clicking a map scrolls to the next one instead of starting the level, and there's a "show replay" button which one would think is a "continue" button.) Given the option to start over, I would probably pay $0.99 for this game. However, due to its short-lived, repetitive gameplay, the game is simply not worth buying at the current price tag of $4.99.

Click a color, then click a station, then click a remove button-the route would auto update and route around the removed building, maintaining the integrity of the route. Just some thoughts. Mini Metro is a very good way to pass 20 minutes. Build a network of rail lines with an ever expanding area and changing stations, trying to keep efficiency to a maximum whilst keeping waiting times manageable. Sounds boring, but is surprisingly satisfying (even when tearing your hair out, hoping that the train can collect the impatient passengers before time runs out). This port/rework of the PC game seems to work well enough, though it can occasionally suffer a bit of slow down if you manage to get 9+ in-game weeks (difficult, and it might also be because I am using an older tablet). Worth the purchase for anyone who likes puzzles and efficiency.

replyContent: Hello Adam, have you tried Mini Metro yet? Your goal is to draw lines between stations (the different points on the city map) so that your trains reach them and all the passengers waiting at each station. The more passengers served the more points you get. You can add more upgrades over time, they will help you to increase your grid. Have fun :)
